  "statement": {
    "markdown": "Given the head of a linked list, determine if the linked list has a cycle in it. A cycle is when a node's next pointer points back to a previous node. To represent this, we will use a list of integers where each integer corresponds to a node's value and the next pointer is represented by the index of the next node in the list. If a node's next pointer points to `null`, it will be represented by `-1`. Your function should return `true` if a cycle is detected and `false` otherwise. For example, given the list `[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]` where `5` points back to `2`, the input would be `5` lines: the length of the list, followed by the values in the list, followed by the indices of the next pointers in the list. In this case, the input would be: `5`, `1`, `2`, `3`, `4`, `5`, `1`, `2`, `3`, `1`, `-1`. The output would be `true` because there is a cycle in the linked list.",
    "inputFormat": "The first line will contain an integer `n`, the number of nodes in the linked list. The next `n` lines will contain the values of the nodes. The next `n` lines will contain the indices of the next pointers in the list. If a node's next pointer points to `null`, it will be represented by `-1`.",
    "outputFormat": "A single line containing `true` if a cycle is detected in the linked list and `false` otherwise.",
    "notes": "",
    "images": [],
